[1] G7 summit: super-spreading event
Date: Sat 19 Jun 2021
Source: News [abridged, edited]
https://inews.co.uk/news/g7-summit-was-super-spreading-event-for-cornwall-as-cases-rocket-2450-after-johnson-and-biden-visit-1060710


Britain's recent G7 summit of world leaders was a superspreader event that has led to a sharp increase in COVID-19 infections in the surrounding communities, according to the latest data.

Cornwall business leaders, politicians and residents are calling for the Government to "save the summer" following a huge rise in COVID-19 infections following the visit from world leaders, their entourages, the world's media and thousands of police last weekend.

Areas of Cornwall where G7 events were focused saw infections rise more than 2000% in the 7 days leading up to the end of the meeting between global leaders .

One concerned local: "It looks like a superspreader event to me, and now it's spreading."

The area around Carbis Bay, where the summit took place, and Falmouth, where the world's media were based along with many of the 6000 of officers policing the event and protesters, are now suffering some of the highest rates of infection in the country.

The rate of COVID-19 infections in Cornwall and the Isles of Scilly during the week to, and including, [13 Jun 2021] has risen from 2.8 per 100 000 people on the Sunday before G7 began to 81.7 per 100 000. This compares to a national average of 77.4 per 100 000.

But it is in the areas most closely linked to G7 events where rates are of particular concern to local health chiefs.

The rate of infection in St Ives and Halsetown has risen 2450% in the 7 day period to 733.2 per 100 000 people in the 7 days to [13 Jun 2021], when the summit came to an end. In the council ward of St Ives East, Lelant & Carbis Bay the rate has risen by 800% to 294.9 per 100 000 people in the same period.

In a number of Falmouth council wards the rates are now more than 500 per 100 000, with Falmouth East hit by a 2000% rise in infections to 600 per 100 000.

As a result of the surge in infections in Cornwall, local leaders are calling on the Government to immediately bring the spread under control with surge testing in high case areas and additional vaccines to immunise younger people, who dominate the hospitality staff in the county.

While only one person is currently being treated for COVID in Cornwall, health chiefs' fear this number will rise significantly due to the lag between infection and hospitalization. The dominant Delta variant, which was originally discovered in India, is twice as likely to result in younger people requiring medical intervention.

On [Fri 18 Jun 2021], the Government authorized surge testing in some areas of Surrey, where levels of infection are significantly lower than in St Ives and Falmouth. However, Downing Street did not respond to questions on whether it would bring in similar measures or local restrictions to help stem the rise in infections in Cornwall.

Kim Conchie, chief executive of the Cornwall Chamber of Commerce, said: "The largely unvaccinated young staff in our hospitality businesses are catching the Delta variant and they and their colleagues are having to isolate as a result. This is closing down pubs, bars and hotels at a frightening rate.

"We need surge testing, and if the Government wants to save the staycation, not only in Cornwall, but across all the holiday destinations in the UK, then perhaps it should look at providing extra doses in places like Cornwall to ensure the hospitality sector isn't being forced to close due to staff shortages caused by COVID infections."

Munira Wilson MP, the Liberal Democrat spokesperson for health, said: "That the conference may have led to a surge in COVID cases is disheartening. It shows we still need to remain aware of the risks of large gatherings and that the Government should stay vigilant.

[Byline: David Parsley]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

[Events with large numbers of individuals from diverse geographic locations, whether sporting events, entertainment, conferences, or political events, are particularly prone to turn into superspreader events. Attendees need to be vaccinated or tested by rapid tests before entry. - Mod.LK]

******
[2] Brazil
Date: Mon 21 Jun 2021
Source: Stat News [abridged, edited]
https://www.statnews.com/category/the-regulars/morning-rounds/


The COVID-19 death toll in Brazil passed 500 000 over the weekend, marking the 2nd-highest official count for one country behind the U.S. -- though experts estimate India has also seen well over that many deaths. Thousands took to the streets across the country this weekend to protest the government's response to the pandemic. ... The country currently averages around 2000 deaths per day, and experts worry it will only get worse. Just 11% of residents have been fully vaccinated as winter begins in the Southern Hemisphere, increasing the risk of infection.

[Byline: Theresa Gaffney]

